{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"10d6e17e-ea58-48a1-88ba-a3f83e4f8523","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically generates crash reports — no `createdump` needed.\n\n**Look here:**\n\n```\n~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/     # user processes\n/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/      # system-wide\n```\n\nCrash reports are `.ips` files (JSON format) containing the backtrace, register state, loaded images, and signal info.\n\n**Quick find:**\n```bash\nls -lt ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/*.ips | head -5\n```\n\n**Tips:**\n- Reports may take a few seconds to appear after the crash.\n- You can also open **Console.app → Crash Reports** to browse them in a GUI.\n- The `.ips` file will contain native frames — if you need to symbolicate .NET runtime frames, you can use `atos` with dSYM symbols from the Microsoft symbol server.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"231fd291-730d-4421-ae9d-071c80feeb25","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, specifically when `createdump` isn't available. This is a knowledge question — I don't need to search a codebase. Let me answer directly.\n\nOn macOS, when a process crashes, the OS automatically generates a crash report (.ips file) in ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports (for user processes) or /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports (for system processes). These are plain-text/JSON crash logs that contain the backtrace, register state, and other info.\n\nFor NativeAOT specifically, `createdump` is not bundled (it's a CoreCLR tool). \n\nThe good news is that macOS still generates crash reports automatically, so I can provide a straightforward answer about where to find them and how to use them for debugging.","outputTokens":417,"requestId":"4182:1EA9D4:6451712:6D88217:69F1636B"},"id":"3f233385-20b6-43b9-ac19-c0a634e162d1","timestamp":"2026-04-29T01:48:37.792Z","parentId":"9350c073-5152-4d4b-b7b2-186e33c57316"}
